'''Brandon John Morrow''' (born [[July 26]], [[1984]] in [[Santa Rosa, California]]) is a [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher (baseball)|pitcher]] for the [[Seattle Mariners]].

Morrow has three primary pitches, a [[fastball]], [[split-finger fastball]], [[changeup]] and a [[curveball]] combination. He can throw for a high velocity, often getting into the mid to high-90's with his fastball, but often struggles with his command.<ref>[http://prospectinsider.wordpress.com/2006/06/06/brandon-morrow-rhp/ Brandon Morrow, RHP] ''prospectinsider.com''</ref> 

He was the third player from the 2006 draft class to pitch in the Majors, the others being [[Andrew Miller (baseball)|Andrew Miller]] with the [[Detroit Tigers]] and [[Joe Smith (pitcher)|Joe Smith]] with the [[New York Mets]]. He became just the seventh player in Mariners' history to make his debut the year after he was drafted.
==Amateur career==
===High school===
Morrow attended [[Rancho Cotate High School]] in [[Rohnert Park, California]]. As a senior he was 9-2 with a 0.61 ERA and had 84 strikeouts in 63 innings. He earned first-team all-league, first-team All-Redwood Empire, first-team All-North Coast Section and second-team all-state honors. He competed for the California All-Stars at the 2002 Sunbelt Classic in [[McAlester, Oklahoma]]. He majored in [[American studies]].

He was selected by the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] in the 40th round, 1200th overall, in the [[2003 Major League Baseball Draft]]. However, he did not sign with the Angels and decided to attend college at [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]].
===College===
He appeared in 19 games with five starts in his Freshman year, going 1-3 with a 6.07 ERA and 18 strikeouts in 30 innings. He picked up the win in relief versus the [[University of California Los Angeles]] on April 25 going one inning, surrendering one hit, and t striking out two. Morrow had three strikeouts in two innings against [[Brigham Young University]] on [[January 30]].

As a Sophomore Morrow made ten appearances with five starts, going 0-1 with a 9.36 ERA and one save. He had 25 strikeouts in 25 innings. He earned his load save on [[March 19]] against the [[University of Hawaii at Hilo]] with three strikeouts in two innings. He threw a career-high five innings with a career-high six strikeouts against the [[Loyola Marymount University]] on [[February 13]]. 

Morrow was named first-team All-[[Pac-10]] his Junior year, going 7-4 with a 2.05 ERA, second in Pac-10. He had 97 strikeouts, fourth in Pac-10. He held opponents to a .211 average good enough for third in Pac-10. Morrow was named National Pitcher of the Week after pitching seven innings, no hits, no runs, one walk and a career-high 12 strikeouts against the [[University of California, Irvine]].

He was a [[Cape Cod League]] All-Star in the {{by|2006}} summer for the [[Yarmouth-Dennis Red Sox]], striking out 24 batters in 15 innings with a 1.84 ERA and three saves. He was named a third-team preseason All-American and the fifth-best professional prospect out of the Cape Cod League by [[Baseball America]].

==Professional career==
===Seattle Mariners===
====2006====
In first professional season in {{by|2006}} he split time between [[Arizona League Mariners]] appearing in seven games and Single-A [[Inland Empire 66ers]] appearing in one game of the [[California League]]. He posted an 0-2 record overall with a 2.25 ERA in 16 innings striking out 17 batters and starting five games. He pitched three hitless innings for Inland Empire during his brief time there.

====2007====
Morrow was invited to [[spring training]] in {{mlby|2007}}. He went 0-1 with a 1.08 ERA in 6 [[Relief pitcher|relief]] appearances and made the major league club. Morrow was considered a long-shot to make the club at the start of spring

He made Major League debut on [[April 3]] against the [[Oakland Athletics]] in one scoreless inning. 

Morrow went 3-4, with a 4.12 ERA in 60 appearances striking out 66 batters and walking 50. He held opposing hitters to a .243 batting average, including .221 against right-handed batters. He set a club rookie record with 18 [[hold|holds]], breaking old record of 13 set by [[Ed Vande Berg]] in {{mlby|1982}}. Morrow had the fourth most appearances by a rookie reliever in club history with 60 and fifth most strikeouts with 66. Among [[American League]] rookie relievers Morrow ranked second in strikeouts, third in appearances and fourth in ERA. 

On [[April 23]] he earned his first major league win against the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], allowing one hit in career-high three and one third innings pitched. He recorded 18 and two thirds consecutive scoreless innings from April 20 to June 8. During the streak he went 2-0 while holding opposing batters to a .103 average. He also recorded another scoreless streak of 17 innings pitched over 15 outings from July 17 to August 24. Morrow held opponents scoreless in 44 of 60 outings.
====2008====
[[File:Brandon Morrow on July 5, 2009.jpg|thumb|200px|cap|Brandon Morrow in {{mlby|2009}}]]
In the off-season prior to the {{mlby|2008}} season, Morrow had been part of trade talks that would have sent him to the [[Baltimore Orioles]] for [[pitcher]] [[Erik Bedard]], who eventually was traded to the Mariners for [[outfielder]] [[Adam Jones (baseball)|Adam Jones]], reliever [[George Sherrill]], and three minor league pitchers. Morrow was not included in the deal.

After missing two weeks of spring training in 2008 due to a sore shoulder<ref>[http://www.kffl.com/player/15027/MLB KFFL - Brandon Morrow, P, Seattle Mariners<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>, Morrow was optioned to the Mariners minor league affiliate Double-A [[West Tenn Diamond Jaxx|West Tennessee]] on [[March 30]]. Morrow was recalled to the Seattle bullpen 17 days afterwards when Mariners starter [[Erik Bedard]] was placed on the 15-day [[disabled list]].<ref>[http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/mariners/2008/04/morrow_called_up.html Mariners Blog | Morrow called up | Seattle Times Newspaper Blog<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> When Seattle's regular [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[J.J. Putz]] became injured on [[June 12]], Morrow took over his duties. Including a closing appearance on [[June 11]], Morrow [[Save (baseball)|saved]] 8 games in 8 tries since then, until [[July 10]] when he gave up two solo [[home run]]s to the [[Oakland Athletics]] to acquire his first blown save. He had only given up 2 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] all year prior to that, and had 40 strikeouts in 36.2 innings pitched, and a very low ERA of 1.76 and WHIP of 0.88. <ref>{{Citation
 | title = ESPN Player Stats
 | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/players/profile?playerId=28734
 | accessdate = 2008-07-06
}}</ref>

On [[August 5]], 2008, Morrow was optioned to Triple-A to become a starting pitcher.<ref>{{Citation
 | title = Seattle Weekly: The Bright Spot in an Awful Season
 | url = http://www.seattleweekly.com/2008-08-13/news/the-bright-spot-in-an-awful-season.php/1
 | accessdate = 2008-08-18
}}</ref>

Morrow made his first MLB start on [[September 5]], 2008, against the [[New York Yankees]]. Morrow went 7 2/3 [[No-hitter|no-hit]] innings in his first major league start and was 4 outs away to being just the 2nd player to throw a no hitter in their MLB starting debut only to see [[pinch hitter]] [[Wilson Betemit]] break it up. The Mariners went onto win the game 3-1 giving Morrow his first win as a starter.<ref>{{Citation
 | title = Seattle Post-Intelligencer: Morrow's first start for M's will be against Yankees
 | url = http://blog.seattlepi.nwsource.com/baseball/archives/147185.asp?source=rss
 | accessdate = 2008-08-30
}}</ref>

====2009====
On [[March 29]], {{mlby|2009}} the Mariners announced that Morrow would no longer be  a [[starting pitcher]]; instead he would move into a relief role with the organization. Morrow, who is a [[diabetic]], acknowledged that his diabetes was a factor in the decision, saying that it was easier to balance his [[blood sugar]] in a relief position.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/baseball/mlb/03/29/mariners.morrow.ap/index.html Morrow Headed to Bullpen] SI.com, March 29, 2009</ref>

Morrow began the season as the [[closer (baseball)|closer]] and notched five saves through the end of April. However, he was placed on the disabled list on [[May 2]] after he developed right biceps tendinitis. [[David Aardsma]] will serve as closer in his absence.<ref>Street, Jim. [http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090502&content_id=4533332&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea Mariners closer Morrow lands on DL], [[Seattle Mariners]]. Published [[May 2]], [[2009]]. Retrieved [[May 3]], [[2009]].</ref>

After coming of the disabled list Morrow made six starts before bring optioned to the Triple-A [[Tacoma Rainiers]] to develop back into a more rounded starting pitcher.<ref>[http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090711&content_id=5827214&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea About face: Morrow returns to Minors] ''mariners.com''</ref>

On [[August 14]] Morrow pitched a four hit shutout against the [[Iowa Cubs]]. During that game Morrow struck out two, walked one and threw 59 of 96 pitches for strikes. Morrow retired 10 straight batters early in the game.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2009665621_taco15.html Brandon Morrow throws four-hit shutout for Rainiers] ''seattletimes.com''</ref>

Morrow won his fifth consecutive decision for Tacoma tossing five scoreless innings to lead the Rainiers to a 4-1 win over the [[Portland Beavers]] on [[August 29]].<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2009772436_taco30.html Brandon Morrow wins again for Rainiers] ''seattletimes.com''</ref> Morrow was removed from the game because of stiffness in his arm.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2009776619_marinotes31.html Mariners Notebook | Brandon Morrow has setback at Tacoma] ''seattletimes.com''</ref> Morrow was apart of the Rainiers' comeback in the PCL Pacific North.

On [[September 9]] Morrow was called-up to the Mariners. He will start at least one game so Manager [[Don Wakamatsu]] can assess Morrow's progress.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090909&content_id=6880948&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea&partnerId=rss_sea Lacking depth, Mariners summon Morrow] ''mariners.com''</ref>

==Personal life==
He is single and resides in [[Phoenix, Arizona]]. His favorite pitcher growing up was [[Pedro Martinez]].<ref>[http://www.tacomaweekly.com/article/3484 Q&A with Brandon Morrow] ''tacomaweekly.com''</ref>

Morrow is a [[Type 1 diabetes|Type 1 diabetic]] who was diagnosed as a senior in high school. He wears an [[insulin pump]] to regulate his [[blood sugar]] levels..<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4034892 Seattle Mariners Pitchers Deal with Diabetes] ESPN, April 2, 2009</ref>

